  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "What does Brain engineers do?",
  "response": "Brain engineers, often known as neuroengineers, are professionals who apply principles from engineering to the study of the brain and the central nervous system. Their work generally involves understanding, enhancing, or repairing neural functions. Key activities and areas of focus for brain engineers include:\n\n1. **Neuroprosthetics**: Developing devices that can replace or augment neural functions, such as cochlear implants, deep brain stimulators, or brain-computer interfaces (BCIs).\n\n2. **Brain-Computer Interfaces (BCIs)**: Creating systems that enable direct communication between the brain and external devices, which can be used for assisting individuals with disabilities, enhancing cognitive processes, or achieving more intuitive control of machines.\n\n3. **Neural Modeling and Simulations**: Building computational models of brain functions to better understand neural processes and to help predict outcomes of neurological diseases or injuries.\n\n4. **Neuroimaging**: Utilizing advanced imaging techniques like MRI, fMRI, PET, and EEG to map and analyze brain activity and structures for both clinical and research purposes.\n\n5. **Neuromodulation**: Developing techniques and devices to modulate neural activity, such as transcranial magnetic stimulation (TMS) and transcranial direct current stimulation (tDCS), which can be used for therapeutic purposes or cognitive enhancement.\n\n6. **Artificial Intelligence (AI) and Machine Learning**: Applying AI and machine learning algorithms to interpret complex neural data, optimize neural interfaces, and model brain functions.\n\n7. **Rehabilitation Engineering**: Creating technologies and systems to aid recovery and improve functionality in individuals who have suffered neurological injuries.\n\n8. **Neurosurgical Tools**: Designing and improving surgical instruments and techniques that aid in procedures involving the brain, such as robotics-assisted surgery or minimally invasive methods.\n\nBrain engineers often collaborate with neuroscientists, medical practitioners, computer scientists, and other specialists to advance research, develop cutting-edge technologies, and ultimately improve patient care and quality of life.",
